hints:
Part (i) shows us that the order of \emph{a} modulo
$\displaystyle 2^{\alpha+2}$ is equal to $\displaystyle 2^{\alpha}$.
Thus each of

\begin{align*}\displaystyle a^{j} \mod{2^{\alpha+2}}\end{align*}

are distinct odd numbers and thus each of the

\begin{align*}\displaystyle (-1)a^{j} \mod{2^{\alpha+2}}\end{align*}

are also distinct odd numbers. Hence it suffices to show that

\begin{align*}\displaystyle (-1)a^{k} \not\equiv a^{j} \mod{2^{\alpha+2}}\end{align*}

for any $\displaystyle 0 \leq j,k \leq 2^{\alpha}-1$ and finish off the
proof with a counting argument.
